Rating: 4
Great flavour, and yes better after sitting for awhile. Skip the water for a very thick sauce (which I prefer). Chunky peanut butter adds a nice texture. Works great with the other sate marinades, not just the one it was designed to accompany.

Rating: 3
I have made this recipe many times, and my guests and co-workers all LOVE it. I just wish I would remember to just use a HIGH QUALITY canned coconut milk, rather then wasting time and energy processing the flaked coconut. The Dipping sauce, I feel, needs a few hours or overnight for the flavors to develop, and it is not a thick sauce, as I like for a sate.

Rating: 2
Since most reviewers said this sauce was too thin, I used 1/2 cup peanut butter. I also used 2 cloves of garlic and will add more pepper in the future (I foolishly thought my kids would eat this so I only used the 1/8 teaspoon). Very good. I will definately make this again and try it out with other dishes.

Rating: 4
I didn't use the recipe for the sate but instead used the sate kambling recipe from penzeys.com and substituted the lamb for 1.5 lbs cubed filet mignon. This sauce was an outstanding compliment. Instead of smooth I used chunky style peanut butter. The sauce was thin but that was not a bad thing since both the sate and the sauce are very flavorful.

